# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: image-sensors-cmos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] An **active-pixel sensor** (**APS**) is an image sensor where each pixel sensor unit cell has a photodetector (typically a pinned photodiode) and one or more active transistors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] APS sensors are used in digital camera technologies such as cell phone cameras, web cameras, most modern digital pocket cameras, most digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLRs), mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras (MILCs), and lensless imaging for, e.g., blood cells.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In a **metal–oxide–semiconductor** (MOS) active-pixel sensor, MOS field-effect transistors (MOSFETs) are used as amplifiers.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] There are different types of APS, including the early NMOS APS and the now much more common complementary MOS (CMOS) APS, also known as the **CMOS sensor**.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS sensors emerged as an alternative to charge-coupled device (CCD) image sensors and eventually outsold them by the mid-2000s.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The term *active pixel sensor* is also used to refer to the individual pixel sensor itself, as opposed to an array of such individuals, the image sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In this case, the image sensor is sometimes called an *active pixel sensor imager* or *active-pixel image sensor*.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] While researching metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, Willard Boyle and George E.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Smith discovered that an electric charge could be stored on a small MOS capacitor, which became the fundamental building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) that they invented in 1969.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] One of the main challenges with CCD technology was its reliance on nearly perfect charge transfer during readout.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] At RCA Laboratories, a research team including Paul K.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Sadasiv in 1969 proposed a solid-state image sensor with scanning circuits using thin-film transistors (TFTs), with photoconductive film used for the photodetector.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A low-resolution "mostly digital" N-channel MOSFET (NMOS) imager with intra-pixel amplification, for an optical mouse application, was demonstrated by Richard F.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Another type of image sensor technology that is related to the APS is the hybrid infrared focal plane array (IRFPA), designed to operate at cryogenic temperatures in the infrared spectrum.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The devices are two chips that are put together like a sandwich: one chip contains detector elements made in InGaAs or HgCdTe, and the other chip is typically made of silicon and is used to read out the photodetectors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The exact date of origin of these devices is classified, but they were in use by the mid-1980s.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A key element of the modern CMOS sensor is the pinned photodiode (PPD).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] It was invented by Nobukazu Teranishi, Hiromitsu Shiraki and Yasuo Ishihara at NEC in 1980, and then publicly reported by Teranishi and Ishihara with A.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Arai in 1982, with the addition of an anti-blooming structure.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The pinned photodiode is a photodetector structure with low lag, low noise, high quantum efficiency and low dark current.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The new photodetector structure invented at NEC was given the name "pinned photodiode" (PPD) by B.C.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In 1987, the PPD began to be incorporated into most CCD sensors, becoming a fixture in consumer electronic video cameras and then digital still cameras.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Since then, the PPD has been used in nearly all CCD sensors and then CMOS sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The precursor to the APS was the passive-pixel sensor (PPS), a type of photodiode array (PDA).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A passive-pixel sensor consists of passive pixels which are read out without amplification, with each pixel consisting of a photodiode and a MOSFET switch.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In a photodiode array, pixels contain a p-n junction, integrated capacitor, and MOSFETs as selection transistors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] This was the basis for the PPS, which had image sensor elements with in-pixel selection transistors, proposed by Peter J.W.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Passive-pixel sensors were being investigated as a solid-state alternative to vacuum-tube imaging devices.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The MOS passive-pixel sensor used just a simple switch in the pixel to read out the photodiode integrated charge.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Pixels were arrayed in a two-dimensional structure, with an access enable wire shared by pixels in the same row, and output wire shared by column.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] At the end of each column was a transistor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Passive-pixel sensors suffered from many limitations, such as high noise, slow readout, and lack of scalability.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Early (1960s–1970s) photodiode arrays with selection transistors within each pixel, along with on-chip multiplexer circuits, were impractically large.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The noise of photodiode arrays was also a limitation to performance, as the photodiode readout bus capacitance resulted in increased read-noise level.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Correlated double sampling (CDS) could also not be used with a photodiode array without external memory.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] It was not possible to fabricate active-pixel sensors with a practical pixel size in the 1970s, due to limited microlithography technology at the time.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Because the MOS process was so variable and MOS transistors had characteristics that changed over time (Vth instability), the CCD's charge-domain operation was more manufacturable and higher performance than MOS passive-pixel sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The active-pixel sensor consists of active pixels, each containing one or more MOSFET amplifiers which convert the photo-generated charge to a voltage, amplify the signal voltage, and reduce noise.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The concept of an active-pixel device was proposed by Peter Noble in 1968.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] He created sensor arrays with active MOS readout amplifiers per pixel, in essentially the modern three-transistor configuration: the buried photodiode-structure, selection transistor and MOS amplifier.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The MOS active-pixel concept was implemented as the charge modulation device (CMD) by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] This was enabled by advances in MOSFET semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels during the 1980s to early 1990s.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The first MOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The term *active pixel sensor* (APS) was coined by Nakamura while working on the CMD active-pixel sensor at Olympus.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The CMD imager had a vertical APS structure, which increases fill-factor (or reduces pixel size) by storing the signal charge under an output NMOS transistor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Other Japanese semiconductor companies soon followed with their own active pixel sensors during the late 1980s to early 1990s.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Between 1988 and 1991, Toshiba developed the "double-gate floating surface transistor" sensor, which had a lateral APS structure, with each pixel containing a buried-channel MOS photogate and a PMOS output amplifier.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Between 1989 and 1992, Canon developed the base-stored image sensor (BASIS), which used a vertical APS structure similar to the Olympus sensor, but with bipolar transistors rather than MOSFETs.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In the early 1990s, American companies began developing practical MOS active pixel sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In 1991, Texas Instruments developed the bulk CMD (BCMD) sensor, which was fabricated at the company's Japanese branch and had a vertical APS structure similar to the Olympus CMD sensor, but was more complex and used PMOS rather than NMOS transistors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] By the late 1980s to early 1990s, the CMOS process was well-established as a well-controlled stable semiconductor manufacturing process and was the baseline process for almost all logic and microprocessors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] There was a resurgence in the use of passive-pixel sensors for low-end imaging applications, while active-pixel sensors began being used for low-resolution high-function applications such as retina simulation and high-energy particle detectors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] However, CCDs continued to have much lower temporal noise and fixed-pattern noise and were the dominant technology for consumer applications such as camcorders as well as for broadcast cameras, where they were displacing video camera tubes.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The CMOS active-pixel sensor, a type of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) image sensor, was developed by Mitsubishi Electric in 1992 and NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] It came after active-pixel sensors that were developed using PMOS technology in Japan by Toshiba.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] It had a lateral APS structure similar to the Toshiba sensor, but was fabricated with CMOS rather than PMOS transistors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] It was the first CMOS sensor with intra-pixel charge transfer.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In 1999, Hyundai Electronics announced the commercial production of a 800x600 color CMOS image sensor based on 4T pixel with a high performance pinned photodiode with integrated ADCs and fabricated in a baseline 0.5 um DRAM process.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Photobit's CMOS sensors found their way into webcams manufactured by Logitech and Intel, before Photobit was purchased by Micron Technology in 2001.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The CMOS sensor with PPD technology was further advanced and refined by R.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] This led to CMOS sensors achieve imaging performance on par with CCD sensors, and later exceeding CCD sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] By 2000, CMOS sensors were used in a variety of applications, including low-cost cameras, PC cameras, fax, multimedia, security, surveillance, and videophones.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The video industry switched to CMOS cameras with the advent of high-definition video (HD video), as the large number of pixels would require significantly higher power consumption with CCD sensors, which would overheat and drain batteries.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Sony in 2007 commercialized CMOS sensors with an original column A/D conversion circuit, for fast, low-noise performance, followed in 2009 by the CMOS back-illuminated sensor (BI sensor), with twice the sensitivity of conventional image sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS sensors went on to have a significant cultural impact, leading to the mass proliferation of digital cameras and camera phones, which bolstered the rise of social media and selfie culture, and impacted social and political movements around the world.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] By 2007, sales of CMOS active-pixel sensors had surpassed CCD sensors, with CMOS sensors accounting for 54% of the global image sensor market at the time.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] By 2012, CMOS sensors increased their share to 74% of the market.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] As of 2017, CMOS sensors account for 89% of global image sensor sales.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In recent years, the CMOS sensor technology has spread to medium-format photography with Phase One being the first to launch a medium format digital back with a Sony-built CMOS sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In 2012, Sony introduced the stacked CMOS BI sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] There have been several research activities ongoing in the field of image sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] One of them is the quanta image sensor (QIS), which might be a paradigm shift in the way we collect images in a camera.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The QIS idea is in its infancy and may never become reality due to the non necessary complexity that is needed to capture an image.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Boyd Fowler of OmniVision is known for his work in CMOS image sensor development.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] He also patented the first CMOS image sensor for inter-oral dental X-rays with clipped corners for better patient comfort.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] By the late 2010s CMOS sensors had largely if not completely replaced CCD sensors, as CMOS sensors can not only be made in existing semiconductor production lines, reducing costs, but they also consume less power, just to name a few advantages.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] HV-CMOS devices are a specialty case of ordinary CMOS sensors used in high-voltage applications (for detection of high-energy particles) like CERN Large Hadron Collider where a high-breakdown voltage up to ~30-120V is necessary.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Such devices are not used for high-voltage switching though.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] HV-CMOS are typically implemented by ~10 μm deep n-doped depletion zone (n-well) of a transistor on a p-type wafer substrate.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] APS pixels solve the speed and scalability issues of the passive-pixel sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] They generally consume less power than CCDs, have less image lag, and require less specialized manufacturing facilities.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Unlike CCDs, APS sensors can combine the image sensor function and image processing functions within the same integrated circuit.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] APS sensors have found markets in many consumer applications, especially camera phones.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] They have also been used in other fields including digital radiography, military ultra high speed image acquisition, security cameras, and optical mice.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Manufacturers include Aptina Imaging (independent spinout from Micron Technology, who purchased Photobit in 2001), Canon, Samsung, STMicroelectronics, Toshiba, OmniVision Technologies, Sony, and Foveon, among others.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS-type APS sensors are typically suited to applications in which packaging, power management, and on-chip processing are important.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS type sensors are widely used, from high-end digital photography down to mobile-phone cameras.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A primary advantage of a CMOS sensor is that it is typically less expensive to produce than a CCD sensor, as the image capturing and image sensing elements can be combined onto the same IC, with simpler construction required.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A CMOS sensor also typically has better control of blooming (that is, of bleeding of photo-charge from an over-exposed pixel into other nearby pixels).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Unlike CCD sensors, CMOS sensors have the ability to reverse the addressing of the sensor elements.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS Sensors with a film speed of ISO 4 million exist.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Since a CMOS sensor typically captures a row at a time within approximately 1/60 or 1/50 of a second (depending on refresh rate) it may result in a rolling shutter effect, where the image is skewed (tilted to the left or right, depending on the direction of camera or subject movement).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] For example, when tracking a car moving at high speed, the car will not be distorted but the background will appear to be tilted.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A frame-transfer CCD sensor or "global shutter" CMOS sensor does not have this problem; instead it captures the entire image at once into a frame store.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A long-standing advantage of CCD sensors has been their capability for capturing images with lower noise.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] With improvements in CMOS technology, this advantage has closed as of 2020, with modern CMOS sensors available capable of outperforming CCD sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The active circuitry in CMOS pixels takes some area on the surface which is not light-sensitive, reducing the photon-detection efficiency of the device (microlenses and back-illuminated sensors can mitigate this problem).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] But the frame-transfer CCD also has about half the non-sensitive area for the frame store nodes, so the relative advantages depend on which types of sensors are being compared.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The standard CMOS APS pixel consists of a photodetector (pinned photodiode), a floating diffusion, and the so-called 4T cell consisting of four CMOS (complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor) transistors, including a transfer gate, reset gate, selection gate and source-follower readout transistor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The use of intrapixel charge transfer can offer lower noise by enabling the use of correlated double sampling (CDS).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The Noble 3T pixel is still sometimes used since the fabrication requirements are less complex.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The 3T pixel comprises the same elements as the 4T pixel except the transfer gate and the photodiode.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The reset transistor, Mrst, acts as a switch to reset the floating diffusion to VRST, which in this case is represented as the gate of the Msf transistor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] When the reset transistor is turned on, the photodiode is effectively connected to the power supply, VRST, clearing all integrated charge.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Since the reset transistor is n-type, the pixel operates in soft reset.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The read-out transistor, Msf, acts as a buffer (specifically, a source follower), an amplifier which allows the pixel voltage to be observed without removing the accumulated charge.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Its power supply, VDD, is typically tied to the power supply of the reset transistor VRST.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The select transistor, Msel, allows a single row of the pixel array to be read by the read-out electronics.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Other innovations of the pixels such as 5T and 6T pixels also exist.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] By adding extra transistors, functions such as global shutter, as opposed to the more common rolling shutter, are possible.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In order to increase the pixel densities, shared-row, four-ways and eight-ways shared read out, and other architectures can be employed.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A variant of the 3T active pixel is the Foveon X3 sensor invented by Dick Merrill.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In this device, three photodiodes are stacked on top of each other using planar fabrication techniques, each photodiode having its own 3T circuit.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Each successive layer acts as a filter for the layer below it shifting the spectrum of absorbed light in successive layers.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] By deconvolving the response of each layered detector, red, green, and blue signals can be reconstructed.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A typical two-dimensional array of pixels is organized into rows and columns.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Pixels in a given row share reset lines, so that a whole row is reset at a time.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The row select lines of each pixel in a row are tied together as well.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The outputs of each pixel in any given column are tied together.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Since only one row is selected at a given time, no competition for the output line occurs.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Further amplifier circuitry is typically on a column basis.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The size of the pixel sensor is often given in height and width, but also in the optical format.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] There are two types of active-pixel sensor (APS) structures, the lateral APS and vertical APS.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] For applications such as large-area digital X-ray imaging, thin-film transistors (TFTs) can also be used in APS architecture.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] However, because of the larger size and lower transconductance gain of TFTs compared with CMOS transistors, it is necessary to have fewer on-pixel TFTs to maintain image resolution and quality at an acceptable level.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A two-transistor APS/PPS architecture has been shown to be promising for APS using amorphous silicon TFTs.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] In the two-transistor APS architecture on the right, TAMP is used as a switched-amplifier integrating functions of both Msf and Msel in the three-transistor APS.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] This results in reduced transistor counts per pixel, as well as increased pixel transconductance gain.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Here, Cpix is the pixel storage capacitance, and it is also used to capacitively couple the addressing pulse of the "Read" to the gate of TAMP for ON-OFF switching.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Such pixel readout circuits work best with low capacitance photoconductor detectors such as amorphous selenium.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Many different pixel designs have been proposed and fabricated.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The standard pixel uses the fewest wires and the fewest, most tightly packed transistors possible for an active pixel.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] It is important that the active circuitry in a pixel take up as little space as possible to allow more room for the photodetector.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] High transistor count hurts fill factor, that is, the percentage of the pixel area that is sensitive to light.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Pixel size can be traded for desirable qualities such as noise reduction or reduced image lag.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Noise is a measure of the accuracy with which the incident light can be measured.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Lag occurs when traces of a previous frame remain in future frames, i.e. the pixel is not fully reset.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The voltage noise variance in a soft-reset (gate-voltage regulated) pixel is $V_{n}^{2}=kT/2C$ , but image lag and fixed pattern noise may be problematic.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Hard reset The pixel via hard reset results in a Johnson–Nyquist noise on the photodiode of $V_{n}^{2}=kT/C$ or $N_{e}={\frac {\sqrt {kTC}}{q}}$ , but prevents image lag, sometimes a desirable tradeoff.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] One way to use hard reset is replace Mrst with a p-type transistor and invert the polarity of the RST signal.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The presence of the p-type device reduces fill factor, as extra space is required between p- and n-devices; it also removes the possibility of using the reset transistor as an overflow anti-blooming drain, which is a commonly exploited benefit of the n-type reset FET.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Another way to achieve hard reset, with the n-type FET, is to lower the voltage of VRST relative to the on-voltage of RST.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] This reduction may reduce headroom, or full-well charge capacity, but does not affect fill factor, unless VDD is then routed on a separate wire with its original voltage.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Techniques such as flushed reset, pseudo-flash reset, and hard-to-soft reset combine soft and hard reset.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The details of these methods differ, but the basic idea is the same.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] First, a hard reset is done, eliminating image lag.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Next, a soft reset is done, causing a low noise reset without adding any lag.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Pseudo-flash reset requires separating VRST from VDD, while the other two techniques add more complicated column circuitry.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Specifically, pseudo-flash reset and hard-to-soft reset both add transistors between the pixel power supplies and the actual VDD.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The result is lower headroom, without affecting fill factor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] A more radical pixel design is the active-reset pixel.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] Active reset can result in much lower noise levels.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/active-pixel-sensor] The tradeoff is a complicated reset scheme, as well as either a much larger pixel or extra column-level circuitry.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] A **Bayer filter** mosaic is a color filter array (CFA) for arranging RGB color filters on a square grid of photosensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Its particular arrangement of color filters is used in most single-chip digital image sensors used in digital cameras, and camcorders to create a color image.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The filter pattern is half green, one quarter red and one quarter blue, hence is also called **BGGR**, **RGBG**, **GRBG**, or **RGGB**.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] It is named after its inventor, Bryce Bayer of Eastman Kodak.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Bayer is also known for his recursively defined matrix used in ordered dithering.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Alternatives to the Bayer filter include both various modifications of colors and arrangement and completely different technologies, such as color co-site sampling, the Foveon X3 sensor, the dichroic mirrors or a transparent diffractive-filter array.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] 3,971,065) in 1976 called the green photosensors *luminance-sensitive elements* and the red and blue ones *chrominance-sensitive elements*.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] He used twice as many green elements as red or blue to mimic the physiology of the human eye.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The luminance perception of the human retina uses M and L cone cells combined, during daylight vision, which are most sensitive to green light.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] These elements are referred to as *sensor elements*, *sensels*, *pixel sensors*, or simply *pixels*; sample values sensed by them, after interpolation, become image pixels.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] At the time Bayer registered his patent, he also proposed to use a cyan-magenta-yellow combination, that is another set of opposite colors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] This arrangement was impractical at the time because the necessary dyes did not exist.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Although digital CMY sensors have appeared in some older digital cameras, all modern consumer digital cameras use RGB sensitive sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The advantage of CMY dyes is that they have an improved light absorption characteristic, but this has been at the cost of lower fidelity conversion to the necessary RGB wavelengths necessary in light emitting displays.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The raw output of Bayer-filter cameras is referred to as a *Bayer pattern* image.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Since each pixel is filtered to record only one of three colors, the data from each pixel cannot fully specify each of the red, green, and blue values on its own.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] To obtain a full-color image, various demosaicing algorithms can be used to interpolate a set of complete red, green, and blue values for each pixel.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] These algorithms make use of the surrounding pixels of the corresponding colors to estimate the values for a particular pixel.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Different algorithms requiring various amounts of computing power result in varying-quality final images.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] This can be done in-camera, producing a JPEG or TIFF image, or outside the camera using the raw data directly from the sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Since the processing power of the camera processor is limited, many photographers prefer to do these operations manually on a personal computer.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The cheaper the camera, the fewer opportunities to influence these functions.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] In professional cameras, image correction functions are completely absent, or they can be turned off.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Recording in Raw-format provides the ability to manually select demosaicing algorithm and control the transformation parameters, which is used not only in consumer photography but also in solving various technical and photometric problems.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Demosaicing can be performed in different ways.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Simple methods interpolate the color value of the pixels of the same color in the neighborhood.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] For example, once the chip has been exposed to an image, each pixel can be read.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] A pixel with a green filter provides an exact measurement of the green component.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The red and blue components for this pixel are obtained from the neighbors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] For a green pixel, two red neighbors can be interpolated to yield the red value, also two blue pixels can be interpolated to yield the blue value.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] This simple approach works well in areas with constant color or smooth gradients, but it can cause artifacts such as color bleeding in areas where there are abrupt changes in color or brightness especially noticeable along sharp edges in the image.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Because of this, other demosaicing methods attempt to identify high-contrast edges and only interpolate along these edges, but not across them.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Other algorithms are based on the assumption that the color of an area in the image is relatively constant even under changing light conditions, so that the color channels are highly correlated with each other.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Therefore, the green channel is interpolated at first then the red and afterwards the blue channel, so that the color ratio red-green respective blue-green are constant.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] There are other methods that make different assumptions about the image content and starting from this attempt to calculate the missing color values.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Images with small-scale detail close to the resolution limit of the digital sensor can be a problem to the demosaicing algorithm, producing a result which does not look like the model.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The most frequent artifact is Moiré, which may appear as repeating patterns, color artifacts or pixels arranged in an unrealistic maze-like pattern.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] A common and unfortunate artifact of Color Filter Array (CFA) interpolation or demosaicing is what is known and seen as false coloring.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Typically this artifact manifests itself along edges, where abrupt or unnatural shifts in color occur as a result of misinterpolating across, rather than along, an edge.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Various methods exist for preventing and removing this false coloring.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Smooth hue transition interpolation is used during the demosaicing to prevent false colors from manifesting themselves in the final image.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] However, there are other algorithms that can remove false colors after demosaicing.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] These have the benefit of removing false coloring artifacts from the image while using a more robust demosaicing algorithm for interpolating the red and blue color planes.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The zippering artifact is another side effect of CFA demosaicing, which also occurs primarily along edges, is known as the zipper effect.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Simply put, zippering is another name for edge blurring that occurs in an on/off pattern along an edge.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] This effect occurs when the demosaicing algorithm averages pixel values over an edge, especially in the red and blue planes, resulting in its characteristic blur.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] As mentioned before, the best methods for preventing this effect are the various algorithms which interpolate along, rather than across image edges.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Pattern recognition interpolation, adaptive color plane interpolation, and directionally weighted interpolation all attempt to prevent zippering by interpolating along edges detected in the image.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] However, even with a theoretically perfect sensor that could capture and distinguish all colors at each photosite, Moiré and other artifacts could still appear.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] This is an unavoidable consequence of any system that samples an otherwise continuous signal at discrete intervals or locations.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] For this reason, most photographic digital sensors incorporate something called an optical low-pass filter (OLPF) or an anti-aliasing (AA) filter.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] This is typically a thin layer directly in front of the sensor, and works by effectively blurring any potentially problematic details that are finer than the resolution of the sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The Bayer filter is almost universal on consumer digital cameras.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Alternatives include the CYGM filter (cyan, yellow, green, magenta) and RGBE filter (red, green, blue, emerald), which require similar demosaicing.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The Foveon X3 sensor (which layers red, green, and blue sensors vertically rather than using a mosaic) and arrangements of three separate CCDs (one for each color) doesn't need demosaicing.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] They present several patterns, but none with a repeating unit as small as the Bayer pattern's 2×2 unit.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Another 2007 U.S. patent filing, by Edward T.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Chang, claims a sensor where "the color filter has a pattern comprising 2×2 blocks of pixels composed of one red, one blue, one green and one transparent pixel," in a configuration intended to include infrared sensitivity for higher overall sensitivity.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Such cells have previously been used in "CMYW" (cyan, magenta, yellow, and white) "RGBW" (red, green, blue, white) sensors, but Kodak has not compared the new filter pattern to them yet.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Fujifilm's EXR color filter array are manufactured in both CCD (SuperCCD) and CMOS (BSI CMOS).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] As with the SuperCCD, the filter itself is rotated 45 degrees.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Unlike conventional Bayer filter designs, there are always two adjacent photosites detecting the same color.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The main reason for this type of array is to contribute to pixel "binning", where two adjacent photosites can be merged, making the sensor itself more "sensitive" to light.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Another reason is for the sensor to record two different exposures, which is then merged to produce an image with greater dynamic range.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The underlying circuitry has two read-out channels that take their information from alternate rows of the sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The result is that it can act like two interleaved sensors, with different exposure times for each half of the photosites.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Half of the photosites can be intentionally underexposed so that they fully capture the brighter areas of the scene.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] This retained highlight information can then be blended in with the output from the other half of the sensor that is recording a 'full' exposure, again making use of the close spacing of similarly colored photosites.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The Fujifilm X-Trans CMOS sensor used in many Fujifilm X-series cameras is claimed to provide better resistance to color moiré than the Bayer filter, and as such they can be made without an anti-aliasing filter.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] This in turn allows cameras using the sensor to achieve a higher resolution with the same megapixel count.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Also, the new design is claimed to reduce the incidence of false colors, by having red, blue and green pixels in each line.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The arrangement of these pixels is also said to provide grain more like film.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] One of main drawbacks for custom patterns is that they may lack full support in third party raw processing software like Adobe Photoshop Lightroom where adding improvements took multiple years.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Sony introduced Quad Bayer color filter array, which first featured in the iPhone 6's front camera released in 2014.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Quad Bayer is similar to Bayer filter, however adjacent 2×2 pixels are the same color, the 4×4 pattern features 4× blue, 4× red, and 8× green.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] For darker scenes, signal processing can combine data from each 2×2 group, essentially like a larger pixel.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] For brighter scenes, signal processing can convert the Quad Bayer into a conventional Bayer filter to achieve higher resolution.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] The pixels in Quad Bayer can be operated in long-time integration and short-time integration to achieve single shot HDR, reducing blending issues.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Quad Bayer is also known as Tetracell by Samsung, 4-cell by OmniVision, and Quad CFA (QCFA) by Qualcomm.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] On March 26, 2019, the Huawei P30 series were announced featuring RYYB Quad Bayer, with the 4×4 pattern featuring 4× blue, 4× red, and 8× yellow.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] On February 12, 2020, the Samsung Galaxy S20 Ultra was announced featuring Nonacell CFA.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/bayer-filter] Nonacell CFA is similar to Bayer filter, however adjacent 3×3 pixels are the same color, the 6×6 pattern features 9× blue, 9× red, and 18× green.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] An **image sensor** or **imager** is a sensor used for imaging.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] It detects and conveys information used to form an image.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] It does so by converting the variable attenuation of light waves (as they pass through or reflect off objects) into signals, small bursts of current that convey the information.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The waves can be light or other electromagnetic radiation.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Image sensors are used in electronic imaging devices of both analog and digital types, which include digital cameras, camera modules, camera phones, optical mouse devices, medical imaging equipment, night vision equipment such as thermal imaging devices, radar, sonar, and others.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] As technology changes, electronic and digital imaging tends to replace chemical and analog imaging.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The two main types of electronic image sensors are the charge-coupled device (CCD) and the active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Both CCD and CMOS sensors are based on metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, with CCDs based on MOS capacitors and CMOS sensors based on MOSFET (MOS field-effect transistor) amplifiers.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Analog sensors for invisible radiation tend to involve vacuum tubes of various kinds, while digital sensors include flat-panel detectors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The two main types of digital image sensors are the charge-coupled device (CCD) and the active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor), fabricated in complementary MOS (CMOS) or N-type MOS (NMOS or Live MOS) technologies.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Both CCD and CMOS sensors are based on the MOS technology, with MOS capacitors being the building blocks of a CCD, and MOSFET amplifiers being the building blocks of a CMOS sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Cameras integrated in small consumer products generally use CMOS sensors, which are usually cheaper and have lower power consumption in battery powered devices than CCDs.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] CCD sensors are used for high end broadcast quality video cameras, and CMOS sensors dominate in still photography and consumer goods where overall cost is a major concern.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Both types of sensor accomplish the same task of capturing light and converting it into electrical signals.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Each cell of a CCD image sensor is an analog device, a pinned photodiode.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] When light strikes the chip it is held as a small electrical charge in each photodiode.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The charges in the line of pixels nearest to the (one or more) output amplifiers are amplified and output, then each line of pixels shifts its charges one line closer to the amplifiers, filling the empty line closest to the amplifiers.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] This process is then repeated until all the lines of pixels have had their charge amplified and output.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] A CMOS image sensor has an amplifier for each pixel compared to the few amplifiers of a CCD.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] This results in less area for the capture of photons than a CCD, but this problem has been overcome by using microlenses in front of each photodiode, which focus light into the photodiode that would have otherwise hit the amplifier and not been detected.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Some CMOS imaging sensors also use back-side illumination to increase the number of photons that hit the photodiode.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] CMOS sensors can potentially be implemented with fewer components, use less power, and/or provide faster readout than CCD sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] They are also less vulnerable to static electricity discharges.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Another design, a hybrid CCD/CMOS architecture (sold under the name "sCMOS") consists of CMOS readout integrated circuits (ROICs) that are bump bonded to a CCD imaging substrate – a technology that was developed for infrared staring arrays and has been adapted to silicon-based detector technology.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] There are many parameters that can be used to evaluate the performance of an image sensor, including dynamic range, signal-to-noise ratio, and low-light sensitivity.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] For sensors of comparable types, the signal-to-noise ratio and dynamic range improve as the size increases.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] It is because in a given integration (exposure) time, more photons hit the pixel with larger area.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Exposure time of image sensors is generally controlled by either a conventional mechanical shutter, as in film cameras, or by an electronic shutter.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Global electronic shuttering is less common, as it requires "storage" circuits to hold charge from the end of the exposure interval until the readout process gets there, typically a few milliseconds later.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Special sensors are used in various applications such as creation of multi-spectral images, video laryngoscopes, gamma cameras, Flat-panel detectors and other sensor arrays for x-rays, microbolometer arrays in thermography, and other highly sensitive arrays for astronomy.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] While in general, digital cameras use a flat sensor, Sony prototyped a curved sensor in 2014 to reduce/eliminate Petzval field curvature that occurs with a flat sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Use of a curved sensor allows a shorter and smaller diameter of the lens with reduced elements and components with greater aperture and reduced light fall-off at the edge of the photo.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Early analog sensors for visible light were video camera tubes.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] They date back to the 1930s, and several types were developed up until the 1980s.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] By the early 1990s, they had been replaced by modern solid-state CCD image sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The basis for modern solid-state image sensors is MOS technology, which originates from the invention of the MOSFET by Mohamed M.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Atalla and Dawon Kahng at Bell Labs in 1959.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Later research on MOS technology led to the development of solid-state semiconductor image sensors, including the charge-coupled device (CCD) and later the active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The passive-pixel sensor (PPS) was the precursor to the active-pixel sensor (APS).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] A PPS consists of passive pixels which are read out without amplification, with each pixel consisting of a photodiode and a MOSFET switch.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] It is a type of photodiode array, with pixels containing a p-n junction, integrated capacitor, and MOSFETs as selection transistors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] These early photodiode arrays were complex and impractical, requiring selection transistors to be fabricated within each pixel, along with on-chip multiplexer circuits.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The noise of photodiode arrays was also a limitation to performance, as the photodiode readout bus capacitance resulted in increased noise level.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] In June 2022, Samsung Electronics announced that it had created a 200 million pixel image sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The 200MP ISOCELL HP3 has 0.56 micrometer pixels with Samsung reporting that previous sensors had 0.64 micrometer pixels, a 12% decrease since 2019.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The new sensor contains 200 million pixels in a 1-by-1.4-inch (25 by 36 mm) lens.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The charge-coupled device (CCD) was invented by Willard S.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] While researching MOS technology, they realized that an electric charge was the analogy of the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The CCD is a semiconductor circuit that was later used in the first digital video cameras for television broadcasting.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Early CCD sensors suffered from shutter lag.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] This was largely resolved with the invention of the pinned photodiode (PPD).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] It was invented by Nobukazu Teranishi, Hiromitsu Shiraki and Yasuo Ishihara at NEC in 1980.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] It was a photodetector structure with low lag, low noise, high quantum efficiency and low dark current.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] In 1987, the PPD began to be incorporated into most CCD devices, becoming a fixture in consumer electronic video cameras and then digital still cameras.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The NMOS active-pixel sensor (APS) was invented by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] This was enabled by advances in MOS semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The first NMOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) was later improved by a group of scientists at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] By 2007, sales of CMOS sensors had surpassed CCD sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] By the 2010s, CMOS sensors largely displaced CCD sensors in all new applications.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The first commercial digital camera, the Cromemco Cyclops in 1975, used a 32×32 MOS image sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] It was a modified MOS dynamic RAM (DRAM) memory chip.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] MOS image sensors are widely used in optical mouse technology.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] The first optical mouse, invented by Richard F.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Lyon at Xerox in 1980, used a 5 μm NMOS integrated circuit sensor chip.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Since the first commercial optical mouse, the IntelliMouse introduced in 1999, most optical mouse devices use CMOS sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] In February 2018, researchers at Dartmouth College announced a new image sensing technology that the researchers call QIS, for Quanta Image Sensor.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/image-sensor] Instead of pixels, QIS chips have what the researchers call "jots." Each jot can detect a single particle of light, called a photon.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] The **quantum efficiency** (**QE**) of a photodetector is a measure of its electrical response to light.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Another name for it is **incident photon to converted electron** (**IPCE**) **ratio**.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] In a charge-coupled device (CCD) or other photodetector, quantum efficiency is the ratio between the number of charge carriers collected at either terminal and the number of photons hitting the device's photoreactive surface.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] As a ratio, QE is dimensionless, but it is closely related to the responsivity, which is expressed in amps per watt.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Since the energy of a photon is inversely proportional to its wavelength, QE is often measured over a range of different wavelengths to characterize a device's efficiency at each photon energy level.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] For typical semiconductor photodetectors, QE drops to zero for photons whose energy is below the band gap.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] A photographic film typically has a QE of much less than 10%, while CCDs can have a QE of well over 90% at some wavelengths.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] A solar cell's quantum efficiency value indicates the amount of current that the cell will produce when irradiated by photons of a particular wavelength.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] If the cell's quantum efficiency is integrated over the whole solar electromagnetic spectrum, one can evaluate the amount of current that the cell will produce when exposed to sunlight.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] The ratio between this energy-production value and the highest possible energy-production value for the cell (i.e., if the QE were 100% over the whole spectrum) gives the cell's overall energy conversion efficiency value.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Note that in the event of multiple exciton generation (MEG), quantum efficiencies of greater than 100% may be achieved since the incident photons have more than twice the band gap energy and can create two or more electron-hole pairs per incident photon.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] The IQE is always larger than the EQE in the visible spectrum.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] A low IQE indicates that the active layer of the solar cell is unable to make good use of the photons, most likely due to poor carrier collection efficiency.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] The external quantum efficiency therefore depends on both the absorption of light and the collection of charges.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Once a photon has been absorbed and has generated an electron-hole pair, these charges must be separated and collected at the junction.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] A "good" material avoids charge recombination.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Charge recombination causes a drop in the external quantum efficiency.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] The ideal quantum efficiency graph has a square shape, where the QE value is fairly constant across the entire spectrum of wavelengths measured.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] However, the QE for most solar cells is reduced because of the effects of recombination, where charge carriers are not able to move into an external circuit.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] The same mechanisms that affect the collection probability also affect the QE.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] For example, modifying the front surface can affect carriers generated near the surface.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Highly doped front surface layers can also cause 'free carrier absorption' which reduces QE in the longer wavelengths.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] And because high-energy (blue) light is absorbed very close to the surface, considerable recombination at the front surface will affect the "blue" portion of the QE.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Similarly, lower energy (green) light is absorbed in the bulk of a solar cell, and a low diffusion length will affect the collection probability from the solar cell bulk, reducing the QE in the green portion of the spectrum.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Generally, solar cells on the market today do not produce much electricity from ultraviolet and infrared light (<400 nm and >1100 nm wavelengths, respectively); these wavelengths of light are either filtered out or are absorbed by the cell, thus heating the cell.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] That heat is wasted energy, and could damage the cell.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Quantum efficiency (QE) is the fraction of photon flux that contributes to the photocurrent in a photodetector or a pixel.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Quantum efficiency is one of the most important parameters used to evaluate the quality of a detector and is often called the spectral response to reflect its wavelength dependence.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] It is defined as the number of signal electrons created per incident photon.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] In some cases it can exceed 100% (i.e. when more than one electron is created per incident photon).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Conventional measurement of the EQE will give the efficiency of the overall device.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] However it is often useful to have a map of the EQE over large area of the device.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] This mapping provides an efficient way to visualize the homogeneity and/or the defects in the sample.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] It was realized by researchers from the Institute of Researcher and Development on Photovoltaic Energy (IRDEP) who calculated the EQE mapping from electroluminescence measurements taken with a hyperspectral imager.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Spectral responsivity is a similar measurement, but it has different units: amperes per watt (A/W); (i.e. how much current comes out of the device per unit of incident light power).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Responsivity is ordinarily specified for monochromatic light (i.e. light of a single wavelength).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Both the quantum efficiency and the responsivity are functions of the photons' wavelength (indicated by the subscript λ).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/quantum-efficiency] Note that the unit W/A (watts per ampere) is equivalent to V (volts).
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] The rolling shutter can be either mechanical or electronic.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] The advantage of this electronic rolling shutter is that the image sensor can continue to gather photons during the acquisition process, thus effectively increasing sensitivity.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] It is found on many digital still and video cameras using CMOS sensors.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] The effect is most noticeable when imaging extreme conditions of motion or the fast flashing of light.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] While some CMOS sensors use a global shutter, the majority found in the consumer market use a rolling shutter.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] CCDs (charge-coupled devices) are alternatives to CMOS sensors, which are generally more sensitive and more expensive.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] CCD-based cameras often use global shutters, which take a snapshot representing a “relative” single instant in time and therefore do not suffer from the motion artifacts caused by rolling shutters.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] The effects of a rolling shutter can prove difficult for visual effects filming.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] The process of matchmoving establishes perspective in a scene based on a single point in time, but this is difficult with a rolling shutter that provides multiple points in time within the same frame.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] Final results depend on the readout speed of the sensor and the nature of the scene being filmed; as a rule of thumb, higher-end cinema cameras will have faster readout speeds and therefore milder rolling shutter artifacts than low-end cameras.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] Images and video that suffer from rolling shutter distortion can be improved by algorithms that do rolling shutter *rectification*, or rolling shutter *compensation*.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] How to do this is an active area of research.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] This effect can be used as a side channel attack to gain secret keys from certain smart card readers: The attacker films the power LED of the reader while the reader is performing a cryptographic operation, then analyzes the video footage to identify brief voltage fluctuations.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] Due to the effect of the rolling shutter, the footage will reveal fluctuations at a resolution several orders of magnitude greater than the frame rate of the video camera.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] With knowledge about the algorithm used and its implementation in the chip, the attacker can then derive the key.
[src:image-sensors-cmos/rolling-shutter] Analyzing video footage is equivalent to measuring power consumption with an oscilloscope, but less invasive.
